        <div>
          <h3>Find the (Design) North Star</h3>
        </div>
        <p>
          The main objective was to help people save money by creating a mobile personal finance app that is motivational and accessible, both in terms of tech-ability and cross-platform use.
          Knowing personal finance can be a prickly area for many people, Ultrant utilizes a very friendly and inviting interface that makes users feel comfortable and accomplished for creating and sticking to their
          financial goals.
        </p>
        <div>
          <picture class="designstrategy">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/design_strategy_@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/design_strategy_@2x.png" alt="Ultrant Design Strategy" />
          </picture>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Research and Discovery </h3>
        </div>
        I conducted research on 2 major competitors in the personal finance space: Ellevest and Mint. Ellevest, seen below on the left, has a professional, yet conversational
        design language that infuses trust into every task. While, Mint, on the other hand, relies on a soothing, cool blue color and easy to understand onboarding information to ensure quick comprehension. I knew
        these were elements I wanted my app to possess as well.
        </p>
        <div>
          <picture class="img">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/competitors@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/competitors@2x.png" alt="Ultrant Competitors" />
          </picture>
        </div>
        <p>
          An MVP for Ultrant already existed and now it was up to me to spruce up the user experience and interface. I focused on 3 key functions listed in the MVP:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>As a new user, I need to be able to create a profile, so that the financial advice I receive is personalized to me, my spending habits, and tailored to my goals.</li>
          <li>As a user, I want the money-saving tool I use to be motivational, so that I stay on track with my goals.</li>
          <li>As a user, I want to receive a personalized savings plan, so that I can save enough money to reach my goal in time.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          With these in mind, I sought to better understand the problem space. I conducted interviews (12 total) to determine other motivations and pain points users experience with their fintech apps. From there I had a much better vision for the
          app and target audience and created personas based on them, seen below. Building further upon the user stories and personas, I created a site map in order to visualize the information hierarchy and provide structure for the app. After that,
          I focused on creating wireframes for the primary flow: adding a personalized goal.
        </p>
        <div>
          <picture class="img">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/user_persona2_@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/user_persona2_@2x.png" alt="persona2" />
          </picture>
        </div>
        <div>
          <picture class="img">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/Ultrant_sketch_@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/Ultrant_sketch_@2x.png" alt="low fidelity sketch" />
          </picture>
        </div>
        <p> The style guide for the project was next. Consumer Affairs reports that only 20% of consumers prefer a visit to a physical bank over a digital experience. Another statistic states that over half of Americans delay making financial
          decisions.
          What this says is there are a lot of individuals looking to have a positive experience with their personal finance tool, and they need a little guidance in making decisions to save and invest their money properly.
          That’s why Ultrant relies on dark blues and friendly illustrations are used to instill trust, calm, and inclusiveness.
          I wanted to combine the calm, professional tone of the fintech industry with the warm and friendly illustrations and casual, creative tone of a mental-health and wellness-type brand.
        </p>
        <p>Bringing it all together, I created a deliverables bundle including low- and high-fidelity wireframes, mobile mockups, a design system, user flows and a plan for potential product add-on features. </p>
        <div>
          <picture class="img">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/Style_guide_@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/Style_guide_@2x.png" alt="style guide" />
          </picture>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3>Final Design: Mission Accomplished</h3>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3>Conclusion</h3>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Areas of Improvement</h4>
        </div>
        <p>
          Being very clear on the design strategy helped the rest of this design fall into place easily later.
          Throughout this process I learned to be more organized with documentation and handoff and more iterative in my design process.
        </p>
        <div>
          <h4>Next Iteration</h4>
        </div>
        <div>
          <picture class="img">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/Our_services_@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/Our_services_@2x.png" alt="Ultrant Services" />
          </picture>
        </div>
        <p> The project met the main design objectives, which are stated again in the image above. The next steps for this project would be to expand testing and functionality.</p>
        <div>
          <picture class="img">
            <source srcset="img/ultrant/superhero_illustration_@1x.png" media="(max-width:767px)" />
            <img src="img/ultrant/superhero_illustration_@2x.png" alt="Ultrant Image" />
